Lemma.  For all x, y : ‚Ñï, x < y iff there exists some z : ‚Ñï such that x + s(z) = y.  [less if add succ]

Proof.  Let x, y : ‚Ñï, and suppose that x < y.  Then x ‚â§ y, so there exists w : ‚Ñï such that x + w = y.  If w = 0 then x + 0 = y, so x = y, which is a contradiction.  So w ‚â† 0, so by [positive is successor] there exists z : ‚Ñï such that w = s(z).  Then x + s(z) = y.

Now suppose that there exists some z : ‚Ñï such that x + s(z) = y.  Then x ‚â§ y.  Suppose that x = y.  Then x + s(z) = x.  We know that x + 0 = x, so x + s(z) = x + 0, so s(z) + x = 0 + x.  Then s(z) = 0, which is a contradiction to [0 is not successor].  So x ‚â† y.  It follows that x < y.

