Theorem (trichotomy).  For all x, y: ‚Ñï, precisely one of x < y or x = y or x > y holds.

Proof.

Let a, b ‚àà ‚Ñï.  Suppose that a < b and a = b.  It then follows that a < a, which is a contradiction to [irreflexivity of <].  Now suppose that a = b and a > b.  It follows that a > a, which is similarly a contradiction.  Now suppose that a < b and b < a.  By [transitivity of <] we deduce that a < a, again a contradiction.

Now let

    G = { x ‚àà ‚Ñï | for all y ‚àà ‚Ñï, x < y or x = y or x > y }.

We will show that x ‚àà G for all x ‚àà ‚Ñï.  We start by showing that 0 ‚àà G.  Let y ‚àà ‚Ñï.  By [all x ‚â• 0] we know that 0 ‚â§ y.  It follows that y = 0 or y > 0.  Hence 0 ‚àà G.

Now let x ‚àà ‚Ñï, and suppose that x ‚àà G.  We will show that s(x) ‚àà G.  Let y ‚àà ‚Ñï.  By hypothesis we know that x < y or x = y or x > y.

First suppose that x < y.  Then there is some p ‚àà ‚Ñï such that x + p = y.  If p = 0, then x = y, so s(x) > y by [all x < s(x)].  If p ‚â† 0, then by [positive is successor] there is some r ‚àà ‚Ñï such that p = s(r), which implies that x + s(r) = y, which implies s(x) + r = y, so s(x) ‚â§ y, so either s(x) < y or s(x) = y.

Next suppose that x = y.  Then by [all x < s(x)] it follows that s(x) > x = y.  Finally, suppose that x > y.  We know that s(x) > x, and by [transitivity of <] it follows that s(x) > y.

Putting the cases together, we see that s(x) < y or s(x) = y or s(x) > y always holds.  Hence s(x) ‚àà G, and we conclude that G = ‚Ñï.

Theorem.  For all x : ‚Ñï, there is no y : ‚Ñï such that x < y < s(x).

Proof.  Let x : ‚Ñï, and assume there is some y : ‚Ñï such that x < y < s(x).  By [less if add succ] there is some u : ‚Ñï such that x + s(u) = y.  Now s(x) + u = x + s(u) = y.  So s(x) ‚â§ y.  But we know that y < s(x).  This is a contradiction to [trichotomy].

Theorem.  Let x, y, z ‚àà ‚Ñï.

    a. x ‚â§ x.
    b. If x < y and y ‚â§ z, then x < z.
